<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 12.3.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
<h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. Aligning Learning with an Implementation Model</h3>

<h3>Implementation Model</h3>
    <p>A <em>public policy </em>is a law, regulation, procedure, administrative action, or voluntary practice of government that affects groups or populations and influences resource allocation.<sup>1</sup></p>
    <p>Literature emphasizes the importance of studying not only policy development but also policy implementation. Dunst et al states that &ldquo;policy implementation concerns itself with strategies used to translate policies into practice, and the analysis of the implementation of existing policies to determine whether they are achieving stated goals or solving the problem(s) that the policy is intended to alleviate.&rdquo;<sup>2</sup></p>
    <p>Robert M. Friedman developed a framework composed of four dimensions to be used in studying public policy development and implementation in children&rsquo;s mental health:  (1) Stages of policy development and implementation, (2) Levels of government at which policy is developed and the interrelationship between the levels, (3) Service sectors or systems affected by policy and the interrelationship between policy in different sectors, and (4) Variables that are likely to affect the level of impact that policy has.</p>
    <p> However, the framework is based on a broad review of policy development and implementation literature. The major reason for embarking on the study of policy development and implementation is because of its relationship to service delivery and, ultimately outcomes for children and families.<sup>3</sup></p>
        <p><img src="../../images/smart-implementation-framework-12.png"  alt="Implementation Framework" /></p>
